Hepatitis: When is the doctor looking for?
Around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C worldwide, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often don’t know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various viruses caused by infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread to two different types: in hepatitis A and E, by the digestive tract (for example, by contaminated foods or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, cervix or speicle).
Travelers are recommended for vaccination against the viruses A and B at any time, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur about two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, stomach pain and fracture.
Afterwards, the yellowness occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the healing can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that estimates are based on only every 10th infection in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: Untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells home-to-home — in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control investigations, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
The number of chronic hepatitis C cases worldwide is currently estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the home doctor in the first signs of unknown origin.
In a timely manner, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing the onset of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time in patients worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its emergence and the importance of early detection.
