The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers seized the idea of the laser-controlled distance knife.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in seconds break parts, and the autoboter immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the author could not respond quickly enough to escape the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the “Mobility Laboratory” and the Autoboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered inevitable.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of bees when they alienate other bees.
This must be done in the fraction of a second.
However, the exhalation, unlike the bees, can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and it can only be in the direction of the veracity of the tyres.
While there are endless opportunities for bees here to escape other bees, the researchers were able to operate only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device needs to process only a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store these, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it currently only requires a handful of KB of memory.
There is no need for a gigabyte and megabyte heavier memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan's assessment, will be serial in production over the next ten years.
